title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: Single cell transcriptomes difficult annotate without extensive knowledge underlying biology system question. Even knowledge, accurate identification can challenging due lack detectable expression common marker genes defined bulk RNA-seq, flow cytometry, single cell RNA-seq platforms, etc. clustifyr solves problem providing functions automatically annotate single cells clusters using bulk RNA-seq data marker gene lists (ranked unranked). Additional functions allow exploratory analysis calculated similarities single cell RNA-seq datasets reference data.

title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: install clustifyr BiocManager must installed.
code: install.packages("BiocManager")  BiocManager::install("clustifyr")

title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: example, take 10x Genomics 3’ scRNA-seq dataset peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) annotate cell clusters (identified using Seurat) using scRNA-seq cell clusters assigned CITE-seq experiment.
code: library(clustifyr) library(ggplot2) library(cowplot)  # Matrix of normalized single-cell RNA-seq counts pbmc_matrix <- clustifyr::pbmc_matrix_small  # meta.data table containing cluster assignments for each cell # The table that we are using also contains the known cell identities in the "classified" column pbmc_meta <- clustifyr::pbmc_meta

title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: identify cell types, clustifyr() function requires several inputs: input: SingleCellExperiment Seurat object matrix normalized single-cell RNA-seq counts metadata: meta.data table containing cluster assignments cell (required Seurat object given) ref_mat: reference matrix containing RNA-seq expression data cell type interest query_genes: list genes use comparison (optional recommended) using matrix scRNA-seq counts clustifyr() return matrix correlation coefficients cell type cluster, rownames corresponding cluster number. visualize clustifyr() results can use plot_cor_heatmap() function plot correlation coefficients cluster cell type.
code: # Calculate correlation coefficients for each cluster (spearman by default) vargenes <- pbmc_vargenes[1:500]  res <- clustify(   input = pbmc_matrix, # matrix of normalized scRNA-seq counts (or SCE/Seurat object)   metadata = pbmc_meta, # meta.data table containing cell clusters   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters", # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters   ref_mat = cbmc_ref, # matrix of RNA-seq expression data for each cell type   query_genes = vargenes # list of highly varible genes identified with Seurat )  # Peek at correlation matrix res[1:5, 1:5] #>           B CD14+ Mono CD16+ Mono     CD34+     CD4 T #> 0 0.6563466  0.6454029  0.6485863 0.7089861 0.8804508 #> 1 0.6394363  0.6388404  0.6569401 0.7027430 0.8488750 #> 2 0.5524081  0.9372089  0.8930158 0.5879264 0.5347312 #> 3 0.8945380  0.5801453  0.6146857 0.6955897 0.6566739 #> 4 0.5711643  0.5623870  0.5826233 0.6280913 0.7467347  # Call cell types res2 <- cor_to_call(   cor_mat = res,                  # matrix correlation coefficients   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters" # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters ) res2[1:5, ] #> # A tibble: 5 × 3 #> # Groups:   seurat_clusters [5] #>   seurat_clusters type           r #>   <chr>           <chr>      <dbl> #> 1 3               B          0.895 #> 2 2               CD14+ Mono 0.937 #> 3 5               CD16+ Mono 0.929 #> 4 0               CD4 T      0.880 #> 5 1               CD4 T      0.849  # Insert into original metadata as "type" column pbmc_meta2 <- call_to_metadata(   res = res2,                     # data.frame of called cell type for each cluster   metadata = pbmc_meta,           # original meta.data table containing cell clusters   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters" # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters ) # Create heatmap of correlation coefficients using clustifyr() output plot_cor_heatmap(cor_mat = res)

what: Plot cluster identities and correlation coefficients
title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: clustifyr also provides functions overlay correlation coefficients pre-calculated tSNE embeddings (dimensionality reduction method).   plot_best_call() function can used label cluster cell type gives highest corelation coefficient. Using plot_dims() function, can also plot known identities cluster, stored “classified” column meta.data table. plots show highest correlations reference RNA-seq data 10x Genomics scRNA-seq dataset restricted correct cell clusters.
code: # Overlay correlation coefficients on UMAPs for the first two cell types corr_umaps <- plot_cor(   cor_mat = res,                     # matrix of correlation coefficients from clustifyr()   metadata = pbmc_meta,              # meta.data table containing UMAP or tSNE data   data_to_plot = colnames(res)[1:2], # name of cell type(s) to plot correlation coefficients   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters"    # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters )  plot_grid(   plotlist = corr_umaps,   rel_widths = c(0.47, 0.53) ) # Label clusters with clustifyr cell identities clustifyr_types <- plot_best_call(   cor_mat = res,          # matrix of correlation coefficients from clustifyr()   metadata = pbmc_meta,   # meta.data table containing UMAP or tSNE data   do_label = TRUE,        # should the feature label be shown on each cluster?   do_legend = FALSE,      # should the legend be shown?   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters" ) +   ggtitle("clustifyr cell types")  # Compare clustifyr results with known cell identities known_types <- plot_dims(   data = pbmc_meta,       # meta.data table containing UMAP or tSNE data   feature = "classified", # name of column in meta.data to color clusters by   do_label = TRUE,        # should the feature label be shown on each cluster?   do_legend = FALSE       # should the legend be shown? ) +   ggtitle("Known cell types")  plot_grid(known_types, clustifyr_types)

what: Classify cells using known marker genes
title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: clustify_lists() function allows cell types assigned based known marker genes. function requires table containing markers cell type interest. Cell types can assigned using several statistical tests including, hypergeometric, Jaccard, Spearman, GSEA.
code: # Take a peek at marker gene table cbmc_m #>   CD4 T CD8 T Memory CD4 T CD14+ Mono Naive CD4 T   NK     B CD16+ Mono #> 1 ITM2A  CD8B        ADCY2     S100A8       CDHR3 GNLY  IGHM     CDKN1C #> 2 TXNIP  CD8A       PTGDR2     S100A9  DICER1-AS1 NKG7 CD79A       HES4 #> 3   AES S100B      CD200R1        LYZ       RAD9A CST7 MS4A1        CKB #>      CD34+ Eryth    Mk    DC   pDCs #> 1   SPINK2   HBM   PF4  ENHO LILRA4 #> 2  C1QTNF4  AHSP  SDPR  CD1E   TPM2 #> 3 KIAA0125   CA1 TUBB1 NDRG2    SCT  # Available metrics include: "hyper", "jaccard", "spearman", "gsea" list_res <- clustify_lists(   input = pbmc_matrix,             # matrix of normalized single-cell RNA-seq counts   metadata = pbmc_meta,            # meta.data table containing cell clusters   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters", # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters   marker = cbmc_m,                 # list of known marker genes   metric = "pct"                   # test to use for assigning cell types )  # View as heatmap, or plot_best_call plot_cor_heatmap(   cor_mat = list_res,              # matrix of correlation coefficients from clustify_lists()   cluster_rows = FALSE,            # cluster by row?   cluster_columns = FALSE,         # cluster by column?   legend_title = "% expressed"     # title of heatmap legend ) # Downstream functions same as clustify() # Call cell types list_res2 <- cor_to_call(   cor_mat = list_res,              # matrix correlation coefficients   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters"  # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters )  # Insert into original metadata as "list_type" column pbmc_meta3 <- call_to_metadata(   res = list_res2,                 # data.frame of called cell type for each cluster   metadata = pbmc_meta,            # original meta.data table containing cell clusters   cluster_col = "seurat_clusters", # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters   rename_prefix = "list_"          # set a prefix for the new column )

title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: clustifyr can also use SingleCellExperiment object input return new SingleCellExperiment object cell types added column colData.
code: res <- clustify(   input = sce_small,          # an SCE object   ref_mat = cbmc_ref,         # matrix of RNA-seq expression data for each cell type   cluster_col = "cell_type1", # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters   obj_out = TRUE              # output SCE object with cell type inserted as "type" column )  SingleCellExperiment::colData(res)[1:10,c("type", "r")] #> DataFrame with 10 rows and 2 columns #>               type                 r #>        <character>         <numeric> #> AZ_A1        CD34+ 0.557678024919381 #> AZ_A10       CD34+ 0.624777701661225 #> AZ_A11       CD4 T 0.695067885340303 #> AZ_A12       CD34+ 0.624777701661225 #> AZ_A2        CD4 T 0.602804908958642 #> AZ_A3        CD34+ 0.557678024919381 #> AZ_A4        CD34+ 0.557678024919381 #> AZ_A5        CD34+ 0.645378073051508 #> AZ_A6        CD4 T 0.695067885340303 #> AZ_A7        CD34+ 0.671644883893203

what: Building reference matrix from single cell expression matrix
title: Introduction to clustifyr
text: simplest form, reference matrix built averaging expression (also includes option take median) single cell RNA-seq expression matrix cluster. log transformed raw count matrices supported. reference data, including tabula muris, code used generate available https://github.com/rnabioco/clustifyrdata Also see list individual downloads https://rnabioco.github.io/clustifyrdata/articles/download_refs.html Additional tutorials https://rnabioco.github.io/clustifyrdata/articles/otherformats.html
code: new_ref_matrix <- average_clusters(   mat = pbmc_matrix,   metadata = pbmc_meta$classified, # or use metadata = pbmc_meta, cluster_col = "classified"   if_log = TRUE                    # whether the expression matrix is already log transformed )  head(new_ref_matrix) #>                 B CD14+ Mono      CD8 T         DC FCGR3A+ Mono #> PPBP   0.09375021 0.28763857 0.35662599 0.06527347    0.2442300 #> LYZ    1.42699419 5.21550849 1.35146753 4.84714962    3.4034309 #> S100A9 0.62123058 4.91453355 0.58823794 2.53310734    2.6277996 #> IGLL5  2.44576997 0.02434753 0.03284986 0.10986617    0.2581198 #> GNLY   0.37877736 0.53592906 2.53161887 0.46959958    0.2903092 #> FTL    3.66698837 5.86217774 3.37056910 4.21848878    5.9518479 #>        Memory CD4 T Naive CD4 T         NK  Platelet #> PPBP     0.06494743  0.04883837 0.00000000 6.0941782 #> LYZ      1.39466552  1.40165143 1.32701580 2.5303912 #> S100A9   0.58080250  0.55679700 0.52098541 1.6775692 #> IGLL5    0.04826212  0.03116080 0.05247669 0.2501642 #> GNLY     0.41001072  0.46041901 4.70481754 0.3845813 #> FTL      3.31062958  3.35611600 3.38471536 4.5508242  # For further convenience, a shortcut function for generating reference matrix from `SingleCellExperiment` or `seurat` object is used. new_ref_matrix_sce <- object_ref(   input = sce_small,               # SCE object   cluster_col = "cell_type1"       # name of column in colData containing cell identities )  new_ref_matrix_v3 <- seurat_ref(   seurat_object = s_small3,        # SeuratV3 object   cluster_col = "RNA_snn_res.1"    # name of column in meta.data containing cell identities )  tail(new_ref_matrix_v3) #>                 0         1        2 #> C12orf75 3.223784 0.4297757 2.305767 #> RARRES3  4.341699 1.7550597 3.794566 #> PCMT1    4.576310 2.8893691 2.223141 #> LAMP1    3.919129 0.9441022 1.565788 #> SPON2    3.670497 1.3182933 3.200796 #> S100B    3.069210 0.0000000 0.000000 # There's also the option to pull UCSC cell browser data. get_ext_reference(cb_url = "http://cells.ucsc.edu/?ds=kidney-atlas%2FFetal_Immune",                   cluster_col = "celltype")

what: Classifier for Single-cell RNA-seq Using Cell Clusters
title: Classifier for Single-cell RNA-seq Using Cell Clusters
text: clustifyr classifies cells clusters single-cell RNA sequencing experiments using reference bulk RNA-seq data sets, sorted microarray expression data, single-cell gene signatures, lists marker genes.

title: Classifier for Single-cell RNA-seq Using Cell Clusters
text: Install Bioconductor version : Install development version :
code: if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))     install.packages("BiocManager")  BiocManager::install("clustifyr") # install.packages("remotes") remotes::install_github("rnabioco/clustifyr")

title: Classifier for Single-cell RNA-seq Using Cell Clusters
text: example use following built-input data: expression matrix single cell RNA-seq data (pbmc_matrix_small) metadata data.frame (pbmc_meta), cluster information stored ("classified") vector variable genes (pbmc_vargenes) matrix mean normalized scRNA-seq UMI counts cell type (cbmc_ref) calculate correlation coefficients plot pre-calculated projection (stored pbmc_meta).  clustify() can take clustered SingleCellExperiment seurat object (v2 v3) assign identities. New reference matrix can made directly SingleCellExperiment Seurat objects well. scRNAseq experiment object types supported well. clustify_lists() handles identity assignment matrix SingleCellExperiment seurat objects based marker gene lists.
code: library(clustifyr)  # calculate correlation res <- clustify(   input = pbmc_matrix_small,   metadata = pbmc_meta$classified,   ref_mat = cbmc_ref,   query_genes = pbmc_vargenes )  # print assignments cor_to_call(res) #> # A tibble: 9 × 3 #> # Groups:   cluster [9] #>   cluster      type           r #>   <chr>        <chr>      <dbl> #> 1 B            B          0.909 #> 2 CD14+ Mono   CD14+ Mono 0.915 #> 3 FCGR3A+ Mono CD16+ Mono 0.929 #> 4 Memory CD4 T CD4 T      0.861 #> 5 Naive CD4 T  CD4 T      0.889 #> 6 DC           DC         0.849 #> 7 Platelet     Mk         0.732 #> 8 CD8 T        NK         0.826 #> 9 NK           NK         0.894  # plot assignments on a projection plot_best_call(   cor_mat = res,   metadata = pbmc_meta,   cluster_col = "classified" ) # for SingleCellExperiment clustify(   input = sce_small,          # an SCE object   ref_mat = cbmc_ref,         # matrix of RNA-seq expression data for each cell type   cluster_col = "cell_type1", # name of column in meta.data containing cell clusters   obj_out = TRUE              # output SCE object with cell type inserted as "type" column )  #> class: SingleCellExperiment  #> dim: 200 200  #> metadata(0): #> assays(2): counts logcounts #> rownames(200): SGIP1 AZIN2 ... TAF12 SNHG3 #> rowData names(10): feature_symbol is_feature_control ... total_counts #>   log10_total_counts #> colnames(200): AZ_A1 AZ_A10 ... HP1502401_E18 HP1502401_E19 #> colData names(35): cell_quality cell_type1 ... type r #> reducedDimNames(0): #> mainExpName: NULL #> altExpNames(0):  library(Seurat) # for Seurat3/4 clustify(   input = s_small3,   cluster_col = "RNA_snn_res.1",   ref_mat = cbmc_ref,   seurat_out = TRUE ) #> An object of class Seurat  #> 230 features across 80 samples within 1 assay  #> Active assay: RNA (230 features, 20 variable features) #>  2 dimensional reductions calculated: pca, tsne  #
